SIMPLE: moil
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Moil
<hw>Moil</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Moiled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Moiling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>moillen</ets> to wet,
OF. <ets>moillier</ets>, <ets>muillier</ets>, F. <ets>mouller</ets>, fr.
(assumed) LL. <ets>molliare</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mollis</ets> soft. See
<er>Mollify</er>.]</ety> <def>To daub; to make dirty; to soil; to
defile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou . . . doest thy mind in dirty pleasures <qex>moil</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Moil
<hw>Moil</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Moil</er> to daub; prob.
from the idea of struggling through the wet.]</ety> <def>To soil one's
self with severe labor; to work with painful effort; to labor; to toil;
to drudge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Moil</qex> not too much under ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now he must <qex>moil</qex> and drudge for one he loathes.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Moil
<hw>Moil</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A spot; a defilement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>moil</qex> of death upon them.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moile</ent>⟦br⟧
